[music]

11
00:01:52,979 --> 00:01:55,607
The Medieval
and Renaissance blade,

12
00:01:55,715 --> 00:01:57,774
a profound
and beautiful object

13
00:01:57,884 --> 00:02:00,978
handcrafted by
master artisans of old.

14
00:02:01,087 --> 00:02:03,817
It is designed to kill.

15
00:02:03,923 --> 00:02:07,415
The truth of the sword
has been shrouded in antiquity

16
00:02:07,527 --> 00:02:10,587
and the Renaissance martial arts
that brought it into being

17
00:02:10,697 --> 00:02:12,528
are long forgotten.

18
00:02:12,632 --> 00:02:15,260
The ancient practitioners
lent us all that they knew

19
00:02:15,368 --> 00:02:17,768
through their manuscripts.

20
00:02:17,871 --> 00:02:20,032
As gunslingers
of the Renaissance

21
00:02:20,140 --> 00:02:23,837
they were the westem heroes
with swords.

22
00:02:23,943 --> 00:02:26,844
They lived and died by them.

23
00:02:26,946 --> 00:02:29,676
Yet today, their history
remains cloaked

24
00:02:29,782 --> 00:02:32,683
under a shadow of legend.

25
00:02:32,785 --> 00:02:34,912
Before the invention
of gunpowder,

26
00:02:35,021 --> 00:02:38,388
the sword was
the weapon of the time.

27
00:02:38,491 --> 00:02:40,959
The sword probably has not
been a relevant weapon

28
00:02:41,060 --> 00:02:42,755
for at least 200 years.

29
00:02:42,862 --> 00:02:48,425
To think that a pummel,
a handgrip, a crossbar, a blade,

30
00:02:48,535 --> 00:02:52,631
a very simple object
could hold such sway

31
00:02:52,739 --> 00:02:56,197
over thousands of years
of human evolution.

32
00:02:56,309 --> 00:02:59,369
These objects have really
controlled our history

33
00:02:59,479 --> 00:03:01,379
and where we are today.

34
00:03:05,285 --> 00:03:07,014
Swords have been used
throughout history

35
00:03:07,120 --> 00:03:10,021
to defend people and land,
to build nations

36
00:03:10,123 --> 00:03:13,217
and to protect kingdoms
from tyranny.

37
00:03:13,326 --> 00:03:15,226
From 1st century wars
against Rome

38
00:03:15,328 --> 00:03:17,455
to the Viking
and Norman conquests,

39
00:03:17,564 --> 00:03:20,362
sword and steel have
changed the fate of kingdoms,

40
00:03:20,466 --> 00:03:25,403
the map of Europe and ultimately
the timeline of world history.

41
00:03:25,505 --> 00:03:28,303
Their essential role
in preserving freedom and honor

42
00:03:28,408 --> 00:03:31,969
goes back far into
the dim mists of history.

43
00:03:32,078 --> 00:03:34,410
The connection between
sword and freedom

44
00:03:34,514 --> 00:03:36,846
may perhaps find its
origin within the customs

45
00:03:36,950 --> 00:03:40,010
of the Germanic
and Celtic tribes.

46
00:03:40,119 --> 00:03:43,680
Here, being armed with a sword
was not only a right

47
00:03:43,790 --> 00:03:47,089
but also a duty
of all free men.

48
00:03:47,193 --> 00:03:49,627
In fact, the ceremony
for giving freedom to a slave

49
00:03:49,729 --> 00:03:51,663
required that
the former slave

50
00:03:51,764 --> 00:03:56,667
be presented with
the armament of a free man.

51
00:03:57,937 --> 00:04:02,499
Many British kings chose to
trust their subjects with arms

52
00:04:02,609 --> 00:04:05,407
and to supplement the militia
in times of need

53
00:04:05,511 --> 00:04:08,105
rather than abolish it.

54
00:04:08,214 --> 00:04:12,275
The idea of a free militia
versus a financed army

55
00:04:12,385 --> 00:04:14,580
presents an interesting concept

56
00:04:14,687 --> 00:04:17,747
that is reflected
in many of our modem films.

57
00:04:17,857 --> 00:04:20,917
The sword is as relevant today
as a symbol

58
00:04:21,027 --> 00:04:24,292
as it was in ages past,
being found within statues,

59
00:04:24,397 --> 00:04:28,993
civic emblems, and insignia
both ancient and modern.

60
00:04:29,102 --> 00:04:32,037
It has been an ancient symbol
for words spoken in truth,

61
00:04:32,138 --> 00:04:36,734
for purity, justice
and the spirit of God.

62
00:04:36,843 --> 00:04:40,711
The iconic power of the sword
is everywhere within our culture

63
00:04:40,813 --> 00:04:43,475
from literature to
popular entertainment and

64
00:04:43,583 --> 00:04:48,885
nowhere is it more celebrated
than in the modern cinema.

65
00:04:53,092 --> 00:04:56,323
There's a definite symbolism
that's part and parcel

66
00:04:56,429 --> 00:04:58,260
of every story
containing a sword.

67
00:04:58,364 --> 00:05:01,856
The sword combines
power, authority,

68
00:05:01,968 --> 00:05:05,495
and the threat of impending
violence all in a prop,

69
00:05:05,605 --> 00:05:07,436
which might be hanging
off somebody's side

70
00:05:07,540 --> 00:05:09,804
until the moment
they draw it.

71
00:05:09,909 --> 00:05:13,436
I think there's something
more intimate about

72
00:05:13,546 --> 00:05:15,446
two guys going at it
with swords.

73
00:05:15,548 --> 00:05:20,178
To fight someone with a sword
as opposed to shooting someone

74
00:05:20,286 --> 00:05:23,187
with a gun, I think
it takes more courage.

75
00:05:23,289 --> 00:05:27,157
It's conflict at its most raw
where you've got two characters

76
00:05:27,260 --> 00:05:30,024
Iooking at each other eye to eye
engaging at that level.

77
00:05:30,129 --> 00:05:32,324
And the stakes are higher
it could go either way.

78
00:05:32,432 --> 00:05:34,400
You are right there in the end
and the sword, in many ways,

79
00:05:34,500 --> 00:05:36,092
is an extension
of that character's arm

80
00:05:36,202 --> 00:05:39,103
so it's really
a sharpened fist.

81
00:05:39,205 --> 00:05:42,140
It suddenly is a realm
of myth, of legend,

82
00:05:42,241 --> 00:05:45,540
of heroes, of adventures.

83
00:05:45,645 --> 00:05:49,274
That would explain to a large
degree the popularity of swords.

84
00:05:49,382 --> 00:05:52,283
They're, you know,
an integral part of it.

85
