784
00:46:49,173 --> 00:46:50,970
For the most part
the ltalian books,

785
00:46:51,074 --> 00:46:53,702
the German books and the Spanish
books on the fighting arts

786
00:46:53,811 --> 00:46:56,575
have been forgotten,
hidden in old libraries

787
00:46:56,680 --> 00:47:00,446
and monasteries in old
archives and universities.

788
00:47:00,551 --> 00:47:03,611
Unfortunately, very little
research had been done on them.

789
00:47:03,720 --> 00:47:05,950
For the most part,
they had not been looked at

790
00:47:06,056 --> 00:47:07,751
for hundreds of years.

791
00:47:07,858 --> 00:47:11,055
Today these old texts are once
again being systematically

792
00:47:11,161 --> 00:47:15,188
studied and the ancient fighting
skills are being reborn.

793
00:47:15,299 --> 00:47:18,132
In the text the old masters
actually request

794
00:47:18,235 --> 00:47:20,965
that the students study
the source literature

795
00:47:21,071 --> 00:47:25,565
and in one instance they ask
that they add to the text,

796
00:47:25,676 --> 00:47:29,373
bringing their own ideas
to it and expanding upon it.

797
00:47:29,479 --> 00:47:33,609
These arts existed in various
forms because they evolved

798
00:47:33,717 --> 00:47:39,087
together hand in hand with
the societies that created them.

799
00:47:39,189 --> 00:47:41,487
There's nothing equivalent to
that in any of the other world's

800
00:47:41,592 --> 00:47:42,752
traditional martial arts.

801
00:47:42,860 --> 00:47:44,919
They don't have the volumes
of technical literature

802
00:47:45,028 --> 00:47:46,017
that we have.

803
00:47:46,129 --> 00:47:47,790
This is our westem tradition.

804
00:47:47,898 --> 00:47:50,423
A lot of people leam martial
arts from people who learned it

805
00:47:50,534 --> 00:47:53,002
from somebody else so often
times it's many generations

806
00:47:53,103 --> 00:47:56,231
removed from someone
with real combat experience.

807
00:47:56,340 --> 00:47:58,865
These books, they're
written by the source.

808
00:47:58,976 --> 00:48:00,739
There's a play in
Wallerstein, specifically,

809
00:48:00,844 --> 00:48:02,038
where the caption
says something like:

810
00:48:02,145 --> 00:48:04,079
The swordsmen have captured
each others' swords.

811
00:48:04,181 --> 00:48:05,512
I thought how that would
never happen in a fight

812
00:48:05,616 --> 00:48:08,244
and I that following week
I was in a bind with a guy who

813
00:48:08,352 --> 00:48:11,685
spun out and we were standing
just like the play showed,

814
00:48:11,788 --> 00:48:13,278
and so that,
all of a sudden,

815
00:48:13,390 --> 00:48:16,723
becomes like a direct
link back to that time.

816
00:48:23,700 --> 00:48:30,230
How did they communicate their
systems to absent third party?

817
00:48:30,340 --> 00:48:34,436
This is combination of words and
images where you have a kind of

818
00:48:34,544 --> 00:48:37,741
notation where you can
almost read the movements

819
00:48:37,848 --> 00:48:39,372
Iike we'd read in music.

820
00:48:39,483 --> 00:48:43,419
It combines a ground plan,
where your feet go,

821
00:48:43,520 --> 00:48:46,489
a representation of how
you hold the weapon.

822
00:48:46,590 --> 00:48:49,525
You can see the relationship
between the swords,

823
00:48:49,626 --> 00:48:52,094
horizontally as well as
vertically because

824
00:48:52,195 --> 00:48:56,655
it casts a shadow and,
of course, scores of postures,

825
00:48:56,767 --> 00:49:00,498
the overall attempt
to convey what the author

826
00:49:00,604 --> 00:49:03,698
wants his student
to understand.

827
00:49:03,807 --> 00:49:05,775
This is the source literature.

828
00:49:05,876 --> 00:49:09,277
This is what's going to tell us
how they did it back then

829
00:49:09,379 --> 00:49:11,939
and this is how we should
be doing it again today.

830
00:49:13,050 --> 00:49:15,041
When one looks at books
on arms and armor,

831
00:49:15,152 --> 00:49:17,712
the incredible detail
and diversity of design

832
00:49:17,821 --> 00:49:20,051
in such weaponry is apparent.

833
00:49:20,157 --> 00:49:22,421
Therefore, it stands to reason
that there should be

834
00:49:22,526 --> 00:49:27,429
an equally sophisticated manner
of using such weapons.

835
00:49:27,531 --> 00:49:30,193
I was inspired by the works
of a gentleman named

836
00:49:30,300 --> 00:49:31,562
Ewart Oakeshott.

837
00:49:31,668 --> 00:49:33,829
Oakeshott was considered
the world's leading authority

838
00:49:33,937 --> 00:49:36,064
on European swords, on
medieval swords in particular.

839
00:49:36,173 --> 00:49:40,735
Most academics look on them
as quaint curiosities,

840
00:49:40,844 --> 00:49:45,508
but they have no real concept
of what that sword was used for

841
00:49:45,615 --> 00:49:47,583
or even how it was used.

842
00:49:47,684 --> 00:49:50,744
Ewart made it into
what it was.

843
00:49:50,854 --> 00:49:53,721
These were weapons
made for young men

844
00:49:53,824 --> 00:49:56,122
to kill other young men;

845
00:49:56,226 --> 00:49:59,024
a real weapon
used by real people.

846
00:49:59,129 --> 00:50:01,757
The typology of the sword
that Ewart Oakeshott devised

847
00:50:01,865 --> 00:50:06,097
included a classification
for all historical blades.

848
00:50:06,203 --> 00:50:10,105
Oakshott's classifications
unlocked the mythical doors that

849
00:50:10,207 --> 00:50:15,110
had obscured the true history
of European martial combat.

850
00:50:26,123 --> 00:50:29,650
I think if you look at any
Anglo Saxon blades, for example,

851
00:50:29,760 --> 00:50:32,957
or Viking blades, ordinary
warriors might have a long knife

852
00:50:33,063 --> 00:50:36,692
and a spear and a shield,
but they don't have the sword.

853
00:50:36,800 --> 00:50:38,199
There are very few swords

854
00:50:38,301 --> 00:50:41,031
in comparison to the number
of axes or spears.

855
00:50:41,138 --> 00:50:43,698
Spearheads and axes
a blacksmith can make.

856
00:50:43,807 --> 00:50:45,866
You have to be a swordsmith
to get the technology

857
00:50:45,976 --> 00:50:50,504
to be able
to make a sword.

858
00:50:50,614 --> 00:50:52,912
I feel a real connection
to the ancient smiths

859
00:50:53,016 --> 00:50:57,043
because I like doing it with
the tools that they had,

860
00:50:57,154 --> 00:51:01,318
with the fuel that they had,
with just clay and water

861
00:51:01,425 --> 00:51:03,325
and a hand hammer
and charcoal.

862
00:51:03,427 --> 00:51:05,520
I have a modern shop, too.

863
00:51:05,629 --> 00:51:08,598
I've got air hammers and
gas forgers and electric kilns

864
00:51:08,698 --> 00:51:11,223
which I used for experimentation
and making sure that

865
00:51:11,334 --> 00:51:13,598
what I think is happening
the ancient way

866
00:51:13,703 --> 00:51:15,864
is actually happening
with some modern tests.

867
00:51:15,972 --> 00:51:17,701
What really affects
me is the chemistry.

868
00:51:17,808 --> 00:51:18,740
Say, "Well how do
they make stuff

869
00:51:18,842 --> 00:51:22,403
from iron sand,
from dirt, basically?"

870
00:51:22,512 --> 00:51:24,639
It's kind of magic.

871
00:51:24,748 --> 00:51:26,147
The more I learned about
it the more I realized

872
00:51:26,249 --> 00:51:27,716
there's different ways
that different cultures

873
00:51:27,818 --> 00:51:29,809
did it so
I had to try that.

874
00:51:29,920 --> 00:51:31,251
I don't like just
reading about it

875
00:51:31,354 --> 00:51:32,412
and putting a book
on the shelf.

876
00:51:32,522 --> 00:51:34,922
I want to do it until l
get it right which causes

877
00:51:35,025 --> 00:51:37,255
a whole lot of sleepless
nights and a lot of work

878
00:51:37,360 --> 00:51:39,419
and a lot of
trial and error.

879
00:51:39,529 --> 00:51:44,592
I feel that a collector
like myself does at least have

880
00:51:44,701 --> 00:51:48,637
some utility to those attempting
to rediscover the sword.

881
00:51:48,738 --> 00:51:52,299
I can provide a swordsmith
such as Paul the opportunity

882
00:51:52,409 --> 00:51:54,707
to make very careful
measurements so that

883
00:51:54,811 --> 00:51:58,577
some of the original swords
which have survived--

884
00:51:58,682 --> 00:52:02,675
rediscovering the way
in which they were put together

885
00:52:02,786 --> 00:52:08,088
to give great performance even
with materials and techniques

886
00:52:08,191 --> 00:52:14,130
that are primitive by today's
technological standards.

887
00:52:16,500 --> 00:52:17,967
Well, sometimes
there is a debate going:

888
00:52:18,068 --> 00:52:19,433
Is the Japanese sword better?

889
00:52:19,536 --> 00:52:20,594
Or the Chinese sword?

890
00:52:20,704 --> 00:52:22,467
Or the Chinese taught
the Japanese their techniques,

891
00:52:22,572 --> 00:52:25,166
so basically it's just
a refined Chinese sword.

892
00:52:25,275 --> 00:52:26,708
Well, no the European
swords are better--

893
00:52:26,810 --> 00:52:29,973
no whoots,
lndian-type blades are better.

894
00:52:30,080 --> 00:52:32,275
I've been working a lot of these
traditions and I'm finding

895
00:52:32,382 --> 00:52:35,317
more similarities of how
they solved their problems

896
00:52:35,418 --> 00:52:36,942
than I am finding differences.

897
00:52:37,053 --> 00:52:38,315
But they have different
ways of doing them,

898
00:52:38,421 --> 00:52:40,116
different ways to stack them.

899
00:52:40,223 --> 00:52:41,247
Some of them using twists

900
00:52:41,358 --> 00:52:43,223
some of them didn't use
twisted steel.

901
00:52:43,326 --> 00:52:45,794
But they solved the problems
in a very similar fashion.

902
00:52:45,896 --> 00:52:47,454
And that really intrigued me.

903
00:52:47,564 --> 00:52:49,031
I figured out some things
that were wrong in books,

904
00:52:49,132 --> 00:52:50,759
things that weren't
written in books,

905
00:52:50,867 --> 00:52:54,860
and other things that I feel are
right by actually doing them

906
00:52:54,971 --> 00:52:57,201
and trying them and testing
the swords and breaking swords,

907
00:52:57,307 --> 00:52:59,468
analyzing things.

908
00:52:59,576 --> 00:53:02,010
I enjoyed getting
primary knowledge.

909
00:53:02,112 --> 00:53:04,512
Definitely people who smelt
their own steel and test

910
00:53:04,614 --> 00:53:08,380
their own blades
and make all things--

911
00:53:08,485 --> 00:53:12,751
Where I feel the connection is
sitting back there with the fire

